I"`

<p>Just as other programs, the git configuration can be divided into three level.</p>

<h3 id="1-configuration-file">1. Configuration File</h3>
<h4 id="11-system-level">1.1 System level</h4>
<ol>
  <li>a file named /etc/config: a file contain values applied to every use in this
 system</li>
  <li>pass –system to git config, it reads and writes from this file</li>
</ol>

<div class="language-shell highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git config <span class="nt">--system</span>
</code></pre></div></div>
<h4 id="12-global-level">1.2 Global level</h4>

<ol>
  <li>a file named ~/.gitconfig: values specifically to you.</li>
  <li>you can make Git read and writes by passing –global option to git config.</li>
</ol>

<div class="language-shell highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git config <span class="nt">--global</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="13-project-level">1.3 Project level</h4>
<ol>
  <li>a file named config, located in the git directory(.git/config): a file
specific to that single repository..</li>
  <li>read from and write to this file with –local option</li>
</ol>

<div class="language-shell highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git config <span class="nt">--local</span>
</code></pre></div></div>

<h3 id="2-set">2. set</h3>
<h4 id="21-your-identity">2.1 Your Identity</h4>
<p>Git commit uses this information</p>

<div class="language-shell highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git config <span class="nt">--global</span> user.name <span class="s2">"Huiyao"</span>
git config <span class="nt">--global</span> user.email zhang@123.com
</code></pre></div></div>

<h4 id="22-your-editor">2.2 Your Editor</h4>
<p>You can configure the default text editor that will be used when Git needs you
to type in a message. If not configured, Git uses your system’s default editor.</p>

<div class="language-shell highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git config <span class="nt">--global</span> core.editor vim
</code></pre></div></div>

<h3 id="3-display">3. display</h3>
<p>Git might read the same configuration variable from more than one file, it’s
possible that you have an unexpected value for one of these values and you don’t
know why. In cases like that, you can query Git as to the origin for that value.</p>

<div class="language-shell highlighter-rouge"><div class="highlight"><pre class="highlight"><code>git config <span class="nt">--list</span>
git config <span class="nt">--show-origin</span> rerere.autoUpdate
</code></pre></div></div>

